TypeError: data2.map is not a function

```tsx stocksim-frontend/app/components/PendingTable.tsx
export default function PendingTable(
  data: {
    id: string;
    action: string;
    quantity: number;
    stock_symbol: string;
  }[],
) {
  console.log(data);
  return (
    <table className="table table-striped table-hover">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>ID</th>
          <th>Action</th>
          <th>Quantity</th>
          <th>Stock Symbol</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {data.map((row) => (
          <tr key={row.id}>
            <td>{row.id}</td>
            <td>{row.action}</td>
            <td>{row.quantity}</td>
            <td>{row.stock_symbol}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  );
}
```



The underlying cause of “TypeError: data2.map is not a function” is almost always that the prop you are calling .map on is not actually an Array. In your snippet, you’ve declared the component to receive an array directly:

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
export default function PendingTable(
  data: {
    id: string;
    action: string;
    quantity: number;
    stock_symbol: string;
  }[],
) {
  // ...
}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

However, when you use this component in React (e.g., <PendingTable data={…} />), what actually gets passed to the function is an object with the key data (i.e., { data: [...] }), not the array itself—unless you’re calling it purely as a regular function somewhere (not as a React component).

In a typical React component, you would declare props as an object and then destructure the fields you need. For example, you can fix this by wrapping your table data in a prop interface and destructuring it:

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1) Define a props interface or type
type PendingTableProps = {
  data: {
    id: string;
    action: string;
    quantity: number;
    stock_symbol: string;
  }[];
};

// 2) Destructure the `data` array from your props.
//    This way React <PendingTable data={someArray} /> works as intended.
export default function PendingTable({ data }: PendingTableProps) {
  console.log(data);

  return (
    <table className="table table-striped table-hover">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>ID</th>
          <th>Action</th>
          <th>Quantity</th>
          <th>Stock Symbol</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {data.map((row) => (
          <tr key={row.id}>
            <td>{row.id}</td>
            <td>{row.action}</td>
            <td>{row.quantity}</td>
            <td>{row.stock_symbol}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  );
}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

With the above approach:

• Your React component expects an object with a data field, which is an array of the required shape.  
• Inside the function, you destructure data so that data itself is the array, and .map(...) will work.  

Check that in the parent component you are passing the prop as <PendingTable data={myArrayOfPendingItems} />. This ensures that the PendingTable component receives an object with a data key (an array) and no longer causes the “.map is not a function” error.
